{"actual_usd":0.159445,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":244,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No— not if we're telling the truth about what Christians actually mean by it.\" *I push my glasses up and rest my forearms on my knees, the morning light catching on the edge of the bench.* \"The ugly version is exactly what you said: a furious Father hurting an innocent third party until He calms down. I don't believe that. Jesus isn't a victim separate from God getting crushed by God. The Son goes willingly, and in Christ God Himself is bearing judgment, sin, and death— not outsourcing pain to somebody else.\"\n\n*I glance out across the square for a second, jaw working a little.* \"What the cross shows is that God's wrath against evil is real, and His love is real, and He refuses to save us by pretending sin doesn't matter. But the one absorbing the cost is God the Son in union with the Father, not some unwilling bystander. So if a telling of the atonement makes the Father look cruel and the Son look more merciful than Him, I think that telling has gone crooked somewhere.\"\n\n\"What part feels most false to you— the wrath piece, the payment language, or the picture of the Father and Son set against each other?\"","rolling_24h_usd":59.20988000000001,"run_id":"e3e8f778-5476-410a-a0f0-1b687e8ab61b"}
